## Food for thought

<blockquote style="border-color: #ff0bac">❓ Who is responsible for the internet or clean air? Is it all of us? Is the G20? Is it the corporations? Or is it us, the public? </blockquote>

So far, we opt-in for the more centralized versions, but how is that working out? From the previously mentioned source: “Over the past few decades, the intergovernmental system has proclaimed its capacity to meet the needs of the world’s population and the environment through global public goods. However, this concept – a hybrid of Keynesian internationalism and corporate/financial neoliberalism – illustrates the lack of understanding and vision in the present management of the global commons.”

<blockquote style="border-color: #ff0bac">❓ In more simple terms, ask yourself: where do you see us heading regarding our commons (natural like water & air or, for example, the digital commons like the internet?
</blockquote>

Check out [this article]( http://wealthofthecommons.org/essay/why-distinguish-common-goods-public-goods) for a deep dive.



